The Italian sign on the left is a demand for a trade union closed shop. Literally: &quot;We ask that the shops are occupied only by unionists.&quot;

The signs with Hebrew letters are likely to be in Yiddish - that was the language of Eastern European Jewish immigrants to the US. Yiddish is written in Hebrew letters, in the same way that English is written in &quot;Roman&quot; letters.

The one on the left has an English message on its other visible side which looks like it is probably something along the lines of &quot;We demand closed shops and open doors&quot;, judging by the message on the Italian sign.
